  },
  "xp_reward": 65,
  "story_variants": {
    "en": "## Vaathiyaar's Combination Lock\n\nVaathiyaar holds a combination lock. \"How many possible combinations are there for a 3-digit lock? What about permutations of letters? `itertools` generates these sequences **lazily**, without storing them all in memory.\"\n\n### itertools Categories\n\n| Category | Functions | Purpose |\n|----------|----------|----------|\n| Combining | `chain`, `product` | Merge or cross-product iterables |\n| Filtering | `islice`, `takewhile` | Slice or filter iterators |\n| Combinatoric | `combinations`, `permutations` | All possible arrangements |\n| Grouping | `groupby` | Group consecutive items |\n\n### Key Examples\n\n```python\nfrom itertools import chain, product, combinations\n\n# chain: merge multiple iterables\nlist(chain([1,2], [3,4]))  # [1, 2, 3, 4]\n\n# product: cartesian product\nlist(product('AB', '12'))  # [('A','1'),('A','2'),('B','1'),('B','2')]\n\n# combinations: n choose k\nlist(combinations('ABC', 2))  # [('A','B'),('A','C'),('B','C')]\n```\n\n> **Key Concept:** All itertools functions return **lazy iterators**. They compute values on demand, making them memory-efficient even for enormous datasets."
  },
